Let $A={ a_(i j) }$ and $B={ b_(i j) }$ be $n times n$
matrices such that $A^(-1)$ exists.

Define $A(t)={ a_(i j)(t) }$ and $B(t)={ b_(i j)(t) }$ by

+ $a_(i j)(t) = a_(i j)$ for $i<n$,
+ $a_(n j)(t) = t a_(n j)$,
+ $b_(i j)(t) = b_(i j)$ for $i<n$, and
+ $b_(n j)(t) = t b_(n j)$.

For example, if $A = mat(1, 2; 3, 4)$, then $A(t) = mat(1, 2; 3t, 4t)$.

Prove that $A(t)^(-1) B(t) = A^(-1) B$ for $t>0$ and any $n$. (Partial credit
will be given for verifying the result for $n=3$.)
